_**Bond purchases and money supply expansion stimulate activity while pressuring [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) valuation**_ through two mechanisms:

Mechanically, interest rate reductions typically weaken currencies. The mechanism operates as follows:

- Generally, ceteris paribus, lowering [interest rates](../../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Interest%20Rate%20Quotations.md) doesn't significantly alter investors' long-term [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) valuation [expectations](../../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Fixed%20Income%20Lecture%20Notes/FORWARD%20RATES%20AND%20TERM%20STRUCTURE.md). The 10-year forward [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) demonstrates minimal movement.
- Reduced interest income due to lower rates creates less attractive [investment](../../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) conditions.
- Market equilibrium requires spot [currency depreciation](../../Principles%20For%20Navigating%20Big%20Debt%20Cycles/Part%20I%20-%20The%20Big%20Debt%20Cycle/Inflationary%20Depressions%20and%20Currency%20Crises/Inflationary%20Depressions%20and%20Currency%20Crises%201.md). This generates greater [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) appreciation potential (reaching the same projected 10-year forward value) compensating for reduced interest income.

The following explanation provides technical detail that some readers may prefer to skip while others will find instructive; proceed according to your [preference](../../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%205%20-%20Modeling%20the%20Preferences%20of%20Individuals/Utility%20Indices.md). Mechanically, interest rate reductions increase [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) forward rates—e.g., one country's 10-year [sovereign risk](../../../../Advanced%20Investments/Lecture%208-%20Inflation%20&%20Sovereign%20Default%20Risk.md)-free bond yield increasing relative to another country's comparable instrument raises the 10-year forward [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md)—so if investors' 10-year [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) valuation remains constant, the spot [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) must depreciate by the present value of the 10-year interest rate differential to maintain stable 10-year forward [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) rates. More precisely and concisely: as explained in Chapter 1, sovereign [interest rate differentials](../../../../Financial%20Markets/Random%20Walks%20in%20Fixed%20Income%20and%20Foreign%20Exchange/Chapter%201/What%20Really%20Is%20the%20Cross-Currency%20Basis.md) between countries are offset by forward [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) premiums—e.g., if Country A's interest rate exceeds Country B's by 2%, Country A's forward [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) trades at 2% annual discount to Country B, so if Country A's [interest rates](../../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Interest%20Rate%20Quotations.md) decrease by 1% from that level while forward [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) remains stable, the [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) would correspondingly depreciate.

Additionally, newly created money can directly exit the [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md), creating selling pressure. As central banks purchase bonds providing cash to other market participants, they may convert this cash to foreign currencies rather than maintaining domestic holdings or purchasing domestic assets/increasing domestic expenditure.

The next table presents various outcome scenarios. The columns continue reflecting private sector lending willingness (decreasing from left to right). The rows represent [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) sensitivity to money supply. As markets increasingly view currencies as inferior value stores, sensitivity to money supply expansion increases due to reduced holding propensity. For example, assuming 1% GDP-equivalent money creation corresponds to ~1% [currency depreciation](../../Principles%20For%20Navigating%20Big%20Debt%20Cycles/Part%20I%20-%20The%20Big%20Debt%20Cycle/Inflationary%20Depressions%20and%20Currency%20Crises/Inflationary%20Depressions%20and%20Currency%20Crises%201.md), our example anticipates ~15% [currency depreciation](../../Principles%20For%20Navigating%20Big%20Debt%20Cycles/Part%20I%20-%20The%20Big%20Debt%20Cycle/Inflationary%20Depressions%20and%20Currency%20Crises/Inflationary%20Depressions%20and%20Currency%20Crises%201.md). **As [currency](../../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) sensitivity to money supply (M0) increases and private sector lending willingness decreases, [currency weakness](../../Chapters/Inflationary%20Depressions%20and%20Currency%20Crises.md) intensifies.**

