## What level of interest rates can make debt burdens affordable for a country?

These examples demonstrate how debt compounds toward unsustainability. I'll now present quantitative parameters for sustainable [debt management](../../Principles%20For%20Navigating%20Big%20Debt%20Cycles/Understanding%20Debt%20Crises%20and%20Their%20Management.md).

For heavily indebted countries with significant deficits, debt and [debt service](../../../../Financial%20Engineering/Notes%20on%20Currency%20Swaps.md) cost trajectories represent major concerns, with growth rates determined by [interest rates](../../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Interest%20Rate%20Quotations.md) relative to income growth and [inflation](../../Principles%20For%20Navigating%20Big%20Debt%20Cycles/Part%20II%20Detailed%20Case%20Studies/German%20Debt%20Crisis%20andHyperinflation%20(1918–1924)/War%20Economies%20and%20Hyperinflation.md), as demonstrated in our calculations. Central banks can prevent rising [debt service](../../../../Financial%20Engineering/Notes%20on%20Currency%20Swaps.md) costs or reduce them relative to [inflation](../../Principles%20For%20Navigating%20Big%20Debt%20Cycles/Part%20II%20Detailed%20Case%20Studies/German%20Debt%20Crisis%20andHyperinflation%20(1918–1924)/War%20Economies%20and%20Hyperinflation.md) and income by suppressing [nominal interest rates](../../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%2010%20-%20The%20Economics%20of%20the%20Term%20Structure%20of%20Interest%20Rates/Real%20and%20Nominal%20Interest%20Rates%20and%20Term%20Struc.md) below nominal growth rates. These relationships impact central government and central bank financial conditions, with broader economic ripple effects that exceed our current focus.

Given these dynamics, we can determine what interest rate would produce specified debt and [debt service](../../../../Financial%20Engineering/Notes%20on%20Currency%20Swaps.md) levels relative to income—e.g., maintaining stable burden, achieving reduction, etc.—based on projected revenue and expenditure.

Hypothetically, as Federal Reserve policymaker, I would evaluate current and projected deficit and debt levels to establish [interest rates](../../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Interest%20Rate%20Quotations.md) preventing excessive future debt burden accumulation. For example, I might target [interest rates](../../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Interest%20Rate%20Quotations.md) maintaining stable [debt service](../../../../Financial%20Engineering/Notes%20on%20Currency%20Swaps.md) payments, influencing my interest rate policy.

I would similarly calculate what [interest rates](../../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Interest%20Rate%20Quotations.md) would prevent significant central bank balance sheet losses.

Let's examine these considerations and their historical applications.

